      ESG: Accounting
   =20
 =20
We  talked yesterday about ESG loans, bank loans in which companies pay a s=
lightly lower interest rate if they meet certain environmental, social and =
governance (ESG) targets, but pay a slightly higher interest rate if they m=
iss those targets. These discounts and penalties are generally quite small,=
 usually one or five basis points in either direction. One can be =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and I was =E2=80=94=C2=A0fairly cynical about this. =E2=80=9CI think =
there is probably a lot of value to be created by telling people soothing t=
hings about ESG,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cand in practice, if someon=
e creates that value, a lot of intermediaries in the chain will capture som=
e of it.=E2=80=9D If you say =E2=80=9Cwe have agreed to do good ESG things,=
 and we have an economic incentive to follow through,=E2=80=9D that is the =
main thing; nobody will necessarily care what the good ESG things are or ho=
w big the incentives are.=C2=A0I also said, you know, there are good reason=
s that the swings are pretty small. If you are a company signing a credit a=
greement, you might want to improve your ESG metrics, but you don=E2=80=99t=
 want to add financial risk; significantly increasing your interest costs f=
or failing to meet some ESG goal seems like a bad financial decision. If yo=
u are a bank, on the other hand, having a big swing between the good-ESG an=
d bad-ESG outcomes creates weird incentives: As an economic matter, wouldn=
=E2=80=99t you always try to buy the ESG loans of companies that will miss =
their targets? Doesn=E2=80=99t that feel bad?But a reader pointed out anoth=
er, stranger aspect of these loans, which is=C2=A0accounting. Basically if =
you are a company you like your borrowing to be accounted for as borrowing.=
 You borrow $100, you add $100 to your assets (as cash) and $100 to your li=
abilities (as long-term debt), you have an interest expense every year, it =
is fairly simple stuff. But some sorts of debt have what are called =E2=80=
=9Cembedded derivatives.=E2=80=9D A classic sort of embedded derivative is =
a structured note issued by an investment bank: The buyer gives the bank $1=
00, and the bank promises that in three years it will pay back, you know, $=
100 plus twice the increase in the S&P 500 index minus half the increase in=
 the price of Tesla stock, or whatever. The bank does not account for that =
as a $100 liability; the bank marks that to market each quarter. Its balanc=
e sheet reflects the fair value of the liability =E2=80=94=C2=A0based on wh=
at the S&P and Tesla did that quarter =E2=80=94=C2=A0and its income stateme=
nt reflects the changes in that fair value. If the S&P goes up and Tesla go=
es down, the bank owes investors more money, so its liability is bigger and=
 it has a loss in earnings.That is an obvious one =E2=80=94 that is a bond =
that is set up explicitly to be a derivative =E2=80=94=C2=A0but a fun game =
for accountants is spotting other, less obvious embedded derivatives. If yo=
u issue a bond or a loan, and there is some unusual provision in it that ch=
anges how much you have to pay in some circumstances, that might be an embe=
dded derivative. Not always =E2=80=94=C2=A0a floating-rate loan based on Li=
bor or whatever, for instance, generally isn=E2=80=99t treated as having an=
 embedded derivative =E2=80=94=C2=A0but a lot of the time.[1] And so if you=
 have some feature like that in a debt contract, some accountant might say =
=E2=80=9Caha, an embedded derivative,=E2=80=9D and make you mark it to mark=
et.And if they say =E2=80=9Caha, your interest rate will change depending o=
n if you hit ESG goals, that=E2=80=99s an embedded derivative,=E2=80=9D the=
n you will have to (1) figure out how much it=E2=80=99s worth, (2) figure o=
ut how much its value=C2=A0changes=C2=A0each quarter, and (3) reflect that =
in earnings. If you hire a few extra white men this quarter, that makes it =
less likely that you will hit your ESG targets, which makes it more likely =
you=E2=80=99ll pay more interest in the future, which increases the value o=
f your liability (the amount you owe), which reduces your earnings for this=
 quarter. In general, if you do bad ESG stuff in a quarter, that will reduc=
e your earnings; if you do good ESG stuff, that will increase your earnings=
.Arguably that=E2=80=99s great! Arguably it is sort of magical and wonderfu=
l for ESG investors to have some mechanism for turning =E2=80=9Cbad ESG stu=
ff=E2=80=9D into a reduction in earnings, and =E2=80=9Cgood ESG stuff=E2=80=
=9D into higher earnings.But in practice it is awfully weird and hard to me=
asure, and it=E2=80=99s not obvious that the specific way that this turns E=
SG performance=C2=A0into earnings is useful for investors. Here is an ISDA =
paper, from this week, called=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAccounting Analysis for ESG-rel=
ated Transactions and the Impact on Derivatives=E2=80=9D; it says that many=
 ESG loans have embedded derivatives under U.S. generally accepted accounti=
ng principles (though arguably not under international financial reporting =
standards[2]) and=C2=A0argues that =E2=80=9Cthe existing accounting framewo=
rks, as they relate to ESG-linked transaction activity, do not provide deci=
sion-useful information to users of the financial statements=E2=80=9D:ESG f=
eatures are currently difficult to value due to a lack of observable inform=
ation that will determine the timing and magnitude of the impact on cashflo=
ws.In most cases, due to the level of estimation and assumptions that are r=
equired, the valuation=C2=A0may not result in decision-useful information f=
or users of financial statements. In practice, many entities view these fea=
tures as having de minimis or immaterial value today, and therefore do not =
recognize the embedded derivative at fair value with changes in fair value =
through earnings. Consequently, the operational burden of analyzing, bifurc=
ating and valuing these features does not result in useful information to t=
he issuers or users of financial statements.The fact that the interest-rate=
 step-ups and step-downs are one or five basis points helps with that: If y=
our cash flows don=E2=80=99t change very much based on ESG performance, you=
 don=E2=80=99t have to do much to account for the future interest cost of y=
our current ESG performance. If your interest rate varied a lot based on hi=
tting climate and diversity targets, you would have a large mark-to-market =
derivative liability, and you=E2=80=99d have to spend a lot of time each qu=
arter thinking about how your ESG performance affected the value of that li=
ability.I don=E2=80=99t know, it is just a fun little puzzle. At some level=
 of abstraction, ESG loans work=C2=A0perfectly=C2=A0with existing accountin=
g rules to give investors and companies and activists exactly what they (sh=
ould) want: An ESG loan gives a company a financial stake in improving its =
ESG performance, and the accounting for that loan lets investors measure, e=
ach quarter, the company=E2=80=99s overall progress on its ESG goals and se=
e how much that progress saves (or costs) the company economically. But in =
reality the result is that companies are like =E2=80=9Cugh I do not want we=
ird accounting stuff to affect my earnings,=E2=80=9D and the result is that=
 ESG loans don=E2=80=99t have much in the way of financial stakes at all.


