you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here=
. Thanks![1] The basic rule is that a risk that is =E2=80=9Cclearly and clo=
sely related=E2=80=9D to the =E2=80=9Chost contract=E2=80=9D (the bond or l=
oan) is not treated as an embedded derivative. (Though the actual relevant =
rule here is that a =E2=80=9Cfloating-rate debt instrument=E2=80=9D is its =
own kind of host instrument and so has no embedded derivative.) Chapter 3 o=
f this PwC memo explains embedded derivatives in more detail.[2] U.S. GAAP,=
 which most U.S. public companies use, is stricter on this point than IFRS,=
 which most non-U.S. companies use. Though here is a Deloitte memo worrying=
 about ESG features under IFRS.[3] Every time I mention this I get a lot of=
 emails arguing about the science of using trees to capture carbon, and whi=
le this is an interesting topic it is=C2=A0=E2=80=A6=C2=A0very much not my =
point here? So, uh, email me if you want, just don=E2=80=99t be like =E2=80=
=9CI demand a correction, actually planting trees does not offset the clima=
te impact of flying to meetings.=E2=80=9D The point is that you can do *som=
ething* to offset the climate impact of the economic activity of your portf=
olio companies, or, at least, it is widely *believed* that you can do somet=
hing to offset that impact. I am using the trees as the most salient and po=
pular approach, though I realize that people have doubts.
