5px;">20% of a picture of a dog</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say you have a thing tha=
t generates cash flows of $1 million a year. A business, a rental building,=
 a pile of credit card receivables, whatever. Let=E2=80=99s say=C2=A0you ca=
n <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24996020.264712/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjIvcHJ=
pdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktZmlybS1nb3QtcmljaC1tYWtpbmctcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktZmlybXMtcm=
ljaA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB168f037d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> capitalize those cash flows</a> at 5%. So th=
e thing is worth $20 million. You want some more money now.=C2=A0You slice =
the thing into shares and sell some of them. You sell 20% of the thing, may=
be. That 20% of the thing comes with cash flows of $200,000 a year and is w=
orth about $4 million. This is all standard stuff; this is the main move in=
 finance. Sometimes it is called =E2=80=9Csecuritization,=E2=80=9D though t=
hat is almost too fancy a title. If you have a business and sell 20% of it,=
 that=E2=80=99s just called =E2=80=9Cstock.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Now let=E2=80=99s say you have bought a picture of a dog online f=
or $4 million. The picture of the dog carries no cash flows and no real exc=
lusive rights =E2=80=94=C2=A0it is just a digital picture of a dog, anyone =
can copy it and use it and look at it to their heart=E2=80=99s content. But=
, you see, you have an exclusive pointer to the dog picture on some blockch=
ain. And it=E2=80=99s funny to =E2=80=9Cown=E2=80=9D this picture of a dog =
on the blockchain. And you made a lot of money investing in crypto and it f=
eels sort of fake anyway. Why not blow $4 million on a picture of a dog, wh=
o cares, easy come easy go.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now you sell =
=E2=80=9Cshares=E2=80=9D of the picture of the dog. How many shares? Who ca=
res? Each share carries precisely no cash flows and no rights to the pictur=
e of the dog, so it doesn=E2=80=99t really matter how many shares you sell.=
 How much are the shares worth? I dunno, I mean, in one sense, you paid $4 =
million for the picture of the dog, so when you slice it into shares their =
total value=C2=A0should be about $4 million. Like, 1% of the picture of the=
 dog should be worth $40,000. Maybe a bit more: Maybe the general logic of =
securitization implies that slicing it into more affordable shares will inc=
rease the pool of potential investors and raise the total value. Maybe a bi=
t less: Maybe the whole point of =E2=80=9Cbuying=E2=80=9D this picture of a=
 dog online is a sort of vanity status thing, and selling it in affordable =
chunks destroys that appeal. You could argue either way, but you would be w=
rong either way, because=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/24996020.264712/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY29pbmRlc2suY29tL21hcmtldHMvMjA=
yMS8wOS8wMi9yZWNvcmQtZG9nZS1uZnQtc2FsZS1oaWdobGlnaHRzLWdyb3dpbmctZGVtYW5kLW=
Zvci1mcmFjdGlvbmFsaXphdGlvbi8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB31ea1cad" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">here is the actual=
 answer</a>=C2=A0(from last week):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Just three months after a non-fungible token (NFT) representing an imag=
e of the original Shiba Inu dogecoin meme sold for about $4 million, the NF=
T is now valued at more than $225 million after part of its ownership sold =
for over 11,000 ether.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors were able =
to boost the price of the doge NFT to a record high for NFTs in such a shor=
t time by fractionalizing it into nearly 17 billion tokens named DOG with 2=
0% of the supply for sale via a 24-hour auction ended Thursday.</p></blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Okay! Look. The fact that the picture of =
the dog originally sold for $4 million is a totally arbitrary fact, driven =
by comedic value and status competition and weird market dynamics among cry=
pto millionaires. The fact that 20% of it sold for $45 million is also tota=
lly arbitrary! There is no=C2=A0reason those two numbers should be related =
to each other at all! Why should 20% of a picture of a dog be worth 20% as =
much as the picture of the dog? Neither of those things is anything! You do=
n=E2=80=99t own the picture of the dog, you don=E2=80=99t own 20% of the pi=
cture of the dog, it is just, like, you come in every day and someone is pl=
aying a new weird game and you try to get the high score in today=E2=80=99s=
 game and tomorrow will be a different game.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Imagine writing the investment memo for =E2=80=9C20% of a picture of a do=
g=E2=80=9D and being like =E2=80=9Cthe most we should pay is probably about=
 $2 million because the whole picture of the dog sold for $4 million three =
months ago and it can=E2=80=99t realistically have appreciated more than 15=
0% since then; even if the whole picture of the dog is worth, aggressively,=
 $10 million, this share would be worth $2 milllion.=E2=80=9D What nonsense=
 that is! I mean obviously by traditional finance standards, but even by bu=
ying-digital-pictures-of-dogs-for-millions-of-dollars standards! Imagine us=
ing logic and comparisons to try to price 20% of a digital picture of a dog=
!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One model here is that everyone on earth =
wants to pay $4 million for a unique picture of a dog, so if you make one u=
nique picture of a dog and sell it for $4 million you=E2=80=99ll get $4 mil=
lion but if you cut it into 17 billion slices each one will sell for $4 mil=
lion? I realize that sentence makes no sense in like nine different ways.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another model is that the value in an NFT co=
mes from a concept, and the value in a fractionalized NFT comes from, like,=
 two concepts. =E2=80=9CTake an object / Do something to it / Do something =
else to it,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/24996020.264712/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubW9tYS5vcmcvY2FsZW5kYXIvZXhoaWJpdGlvbnMv=
MTU0OQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB880abff2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">Jasper Johns wrote</a>. The essential tran=
saction in an NFT is:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>S=
eller:</strong> I will sell you a unique pointer to an image of a dog for $=
4 million.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Buyer: </strong>Ahahaha =
good one, that joke is worth $4 million to me, here you go.</p></blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a fractionalized NFT you have a slightly r=
icher context:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Owner/se=
curitizer:</strong> I bought this unique pointer to an image of a dog for $=
4 million.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>The public:</strong> Aha=
haha good one, congrats, money well spent.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
<strong>Owner/securitizer:</strong>=C2=A0Also I will=C2=A0sell fractional o=
wnership interests in it for like $225 million.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;"><strong>The public:</strong> Ahahaha another good one, that joke is wo=
rth $225 million to us, here you go.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>two=C2=A0</em>jokes so it=E2=80=99s worth 55 t=
imes as much. I don=E2=80=99t know!=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A=
lso it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24996020.26=
4712/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMDMvbm=
Z0cy1ib29tLWFuZXctYXMtZG9nLWNvaW4tYmVjb21lcy01NTAtbWlsbGlvbi1hc3NldC1vdmVyb=
mlnaHQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe655daac" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> doubled the next day</a>?</p><blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The frenzy for digital artwork is breaking new=
 ground as one of the Internet=E2=80=99s best-known memes gets turned into =
a near $550 million asset overnight.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
The DOG coin -- a fraction of the non-fungible token depicting the famous D=
oge meme -- has doubled in value in less than 24 hours of trading, accordin=
g to CoinGecko data. That makes it one of the most valuable NFTs yet.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">PleasrDAO, the art collective that bought the NF=
T for about $4 million in June, started offering fractionalized ownership i=
n the form of $DOG on Wednesday. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
With 17 billion in existence, each DOG coin is worth about 3 cents and abou=
t one-fifth is in circulation, while 55% is owned by the original buyer.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s from last w=
eek; it has since <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
24996020.264712/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY29pbmdlY2tvLmNvbS9lbi9jb2lucy90aGUtZG9nZS1=
uZnQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8e39e6f8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">fallen back to about 1.3 cents</a>. I am so t=
ired. Think about how many productive assets you could buy for $45 million!=
 You bought 20% of a picture of a dog!</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"=
100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">ESG: Accounting</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/24996020.264712/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMDgvbGVuZGluZy1iaXRjb2lucy1pcy10cmlja3k/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd0262fdc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> talked yesterday</a> about ESG loans, bank loans in w=
hich companies pay a slightly lower interest rate if they meet certain envi=
ronmental, social and governance (ESG) targets, but pay a slightly higher i=
nterest rate if they miss those targets. These discounts and penalties are =
generally quite small, usually one or five basis points in either direction=
. One can be =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I was =E2=80=94=C2=A0fairly cynical about t=
his. =E2=80=9CI think there is probably a lot of value to be created by <em=
>telling people soothing things about ESG</em>,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cand in practice, if someone creates that value, a lot of intermediari=
es in the chain will capture some of it.=E2=80=9D If you say =E2=80=9Cwe ha=
ve agreed to do good ESG things, and we have an economic incentive to follo=
w through,=E2=80=9D that is the main thing; nobody will necessarily care wh=
at the good ESG things are or how big the incentives are.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I also said, you know, there are good reasons that the=
 swings are pretty small. If you are a company signing a credit agreement, =
you might want to improve your ESG metrics, but you don=E2=80=99t want to a=
dd financial risk; significantly increasing your interest costs for failing=
 to meet some ESG goal seems like a bad financial decision. If you are a ba=
nk, on the other hand, having a big swing between the good-ESG and bad-ESG =
outcomes creates weird incentives: As an economic matter, wouldn=E2=80=99t =
you always try to buy the ESG loans of companies that will miss their targe=
ts? Doesn=E2=80=99t that feel bad?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But a re=
ader pointed out another, stranger aspect of these loans, which is=C2=A0<em=
>accounting</em>. Basically if you are a company you like your borrowing to=
 be accounted for as borrowing. You borrow $100, you add $100 to your asset=
s (as cash) and $100 to your liabilities (as long-term debt), you have an i=
nterest expense every year, it is fairly simple stuff. But some sorts of de=
bt have what are called =E2=80=9Cembedded derivatives.=E2=80=9D A classic s=
ort of embedded derivative is a structured note issued by an investment ban=
k: The buyer gives the bank $100, and the bank promises that in three years=
 it will pay back, you know, $100 plus twice the increase in the S&amp;P 50=
0 index minus half the increase in the price of Tesla stock, or whatever. T=
he bank does not account for that as a $100 liability; the bank marks that =
to market each quarter. Its balance sheet reflects the fair value of the li=
ability =E2=80=94=C2=A0based on what the S&amp;P and Tesla did that quarter=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0and its income statement reflects the changes in that fair =
value. If the S&amp;P goes up and Tesla goes down, the bank owes investors =
more money, so its liability is bigger and it has a loss in earnings.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is an obvious one =E2=80=94 that is a bond =
that is set up explicitly to be a derivative =E2=80=94=C2=A0but a fun game =
for accountants is spotting other, less obvious embedded derivatives. If yo=
u issue a bond or a loan, and there is some unusual provision in it that ch=
anges how much you have to pay in some circumstances, that might be an embe=
dded derivative. Not always =E2=80=94=C2=A0a floating-rate loan based on Li=
bor or whatever, for instance, generally isn=E2=80=99t treated as having an=
 embedded derivative =E2=80=94=C2=A0but a lot of the time.[1] And so if you=
 have some feature like that in a debt contract, some accountant might say =
=E2=80=9Caha, an embedded derivative,=E2=80=9D and make you mark it to mark=
et.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And if they say =E2=80=9Caha, your inte=
rest rate will change depending on if you hit ESG goals, that=E2=80=99s an =
embedded derivative,=E2=80=9D then you will have to (1) figure out how much=
 it=E2=80=99s worth, (2) figure out how much its value=C2=A0<em>changes=C2=
=A0</em>each quarter, and (3) reflect that in earnings. If you hire a few e=
xtra white men this quarter, that makes it less likely that you will hit yo=
ur ESG targets, which makes it more likely you=E2=80=99ll pay more interest=
 in the future, which increases the value of your liability (the amount you=
 owe), which reduces your earnings for this quarter. In general, if you do =
bad ESG stuff in a quarter, that will reduce your earnings; if you do good =
ESG stuff, that will increase your earnings.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Arguably that=E2=80=99s great! Arguably it is sort of magical and wonderf=
ul for ESG investors to have some mechanism for turning =E2=80=9Cbad ESG st=
uff=E2=80=9D into a reduction in earnings, and =E2=80=9Cgood ESG stuff=E2=
=80=9D into higher earnings.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in practic=
e it is awfully weird and hard to measure, and it=E2=80=99s not obvious tha=
t the specific way that this turns ESG performance=C2=A0into earnings is us=
eful for investors. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/24996020.264712/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaXNkYS5vcmcvMjAyMS8wOS8wNy9hY2Nvd=
W50aW5nLWFuYWx5c2lzLWZvci1lc2ctcmVsYXRlZC10cmFuc2FjdGlvbnMtYW5kLXRoZS1pbXBh=
Y3Qtb24tZGVyaXZhdGl2ZXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd71d5da9" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">an ISDA paper</a>, from th=
is week, called=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAccounting Analysis for ESG-related Transacti=
ons and the Impact on Derivatives=E2=80=9D; it says that many ESG loans hav=
e embedded derivatives under U.S. generally accepted accounting principles =
(though arguably not under international financial reporting standards[2]) =
and=C2=A0argues that =E2=80=9Cthe existing accounting frameworks, as they r=
elate to ESG-linked transaction activity, do not provide decision-useful in=
formation to users of the financial statements=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">ESG features are currently difficult to value due=
 to a lack of observable information that will determine the timing and mag=
nitude of the impact on cashflows.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In most =
cases, due to the level of estimation and assumptions that are required, th=
e valuation=C2=A0may not result in decision-useful information for users of=
 financial statements. In practice, many entities view these features as ha=
ving de minimis or immaterial value today, and therefore do not recognize t=
he embedded derivative at fair value with changes in fair value through ear=
nings. Consequently, the operational burden of analyzing, bifurcating and v=
aluing these features does not result in useful information to the issuers =
or users of financial statements.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">The fact that the interest-rate step-ups and step-downs are one or five=
 basis points helps with that: If your cash flows don=E2=80=99t change very=
 much based on ESG performance, you don=E2=80=99t have to do much to accoun=
t for the future interest cost of your current ESG performance. If your int=
erest rate varied a lot based on hitting climate and diversity targets, you=
 would have a large mark-to-market derivative liability, and you=E2=80=99d =
have to spend a lot of time each quarter thinking about how your ESG perfor=
mance affected the value of that liability.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>I don=E2=80=99t know, it is just a fun little puzzle. At some level of abs=
traction, ESG loans work=C2=A0<em>perfectly=C2=A0</em>with existing account=
ing rules to give investors and companies and activists exactly what they (=
should) want: An ESG loan gives a company a financial stake in improving it=
s ESG performance, and the accounting for that loan lets investors measure,=
 each quarter, the company=E2=80=99s overall progress on its ESG goals and =
see how much that progress saves (or costs) the company economically. But i=
n reality the result is that companies are like =E2=80=9Cugh I do not want =
weird accounting stuff to affect my earnings,=E2=80=9D and the result is th=
at ESG loans don=E2=80=99t have much in the way of financial stakes at all.=
</p>
